lates luminance but in my tests there was only one difference I could find (#9ACD32).","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1,"offset":4014},"end":{"line":48,"column":121,"offset":4134}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1,"offset":4014},"end":{"line":48,"column":121,"offset":4134}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Measured contrast ratios","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":4,"offset":4139},"end":{"line":50,"column":28,"offset":4163}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1,"offset":4136},"end":{"line":50,"column":28,"offset":4163}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So none of the simple methods work and using only black and white text is somewhat limiting anyway. What if we could measure the contrast ratios and progressively increase the lightness and darkness until a desired contrast ratio is met?","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1,"offset":4165},"end":{"line":52,"column":238,"offset":4402}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1,"offset":4165},"end":{"line":52,"column":238,"offset":4402}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Wait, we can do that! In this demo the acceptable contrast ratio is set to 4.5 (WCAG AA compliance). If the desired contrast ratio can not be met, either black or white is returned using the luminance method.","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1,"offset":4404},"end":{"line":54,"column":209,"offset":4612}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1,"offset":4404},"end":{"line":54,"column":209,"offset":4612}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I believe this method is by far the most useful. It can take a little time to compile, although in most situations you probably won't notice and if you